   Of dementia subtypes, Alzheimer's disease (AD) is the most common. Dementia with Lewy bodies (DLB) is thought to be the second most common subtype. DLB's typical symptoms include cognitive impairment, visual hallucinations, spontaneous parkinsonism, and fluctuating confusion. Supportive features include a variety of sleep disruptions that may occur before manifestations of dementia. Psychiatric symptoms include vivid visual hallucinations and depression. The clinical features of DLB are strikingly similar to those of dementia in Parkin's disease (PD).
